#Overview DDSAnalytics is an analytics company that specializes in talent management solutions for Fortune 100 companies. Talent management is defined as the iterative process of developing and retaining employees. Talent management includes: • workforce planning, • employee training programs, • identifying high-potential employees • reducing/preventing voluntary employee turnover (attrition). To gain a competitive edge over its competition, DDSAnalytics is planning to leverage data science for talent management. The executive leadership has identified predicting employee turnover as its first application of data science for talent management. Before the business greenlights the project, they have tasked your data science team to conduct an analysis of existing employee data. Audience is the CEO and CFO of Frito Lay (your client). The CEO is a statistician and the CFO has had only one class in statistics.

#Analysis

You have been given a dataset (CaseStudy2-data.csv) to do a data analysis to identify factors that lead to attrition.
• Identify the top three factors that contribute to turnover (backed up by evidence provided by analysis). • There may or may not be a need to create derived attributes/variables/features. • Identify any job role specific trends that may exist in the data set (e.g., “Data Scientists have the highest job satisfaction”) • Provide any other interesting trends and observations from your analysis. • The analysis should be backed up by robust experimentation and appropriate visualization. Experiments and analysis must be conducted in R. • Build a model to predict attrition.

#Performance Rating We are only interested in retention of employees with a 3 or 4 performance rating, since performance ratings of under 3 are likely on a performance plan or have been terminated. Employees with a 3 performance rating had 15.85% attrition. Employees with a 4 performance rating had a slightly higher percentage with 17.24% leaving. While factors like star performers being recruited to other companies could play a part in the increase, the slight difference in percentage is not significant according to Pearson’s chi-sq test (p=.74).

CaseStudy2 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x= PerformanceRating, fill = Attrition)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "count") + scale_fill_manual(values = colors2) + 
  ggtitle("Percentage of Attrition by Performance Rating") + ylab("Employee Count")

``` #Department & JobRole

There is a relationship between department and attrition (X-squared = 9.329, df = 2, p-value = 0.009424). There is an even more significant relationship between job role and attrition(X-squared = 60.543, p-value = 3.647e-10), with the lowest percentage being 1.96% of Research Directors leaving versus 45.86% of sales representatives leaving. The national trend for sales representative attrition is 27%, which makes this number higher than expected.

Healthcare Representative - 10.5% Human Resources - 22.2% Laboratory Technician - 19.6% Manager - 7.84% Manufacturing Director - 2.29% Research Director - 1.96% Research Scientist - 18.6% Sales Executive - 16.5% Sales Representative - 45.28%

#Age I converted the numeric age to factor. There is evidence(Pearson’s chi-squared X-squared = 27.929, df = 4, p-value = 1.289e-05) that younger or early career employees are not sticking around with 30% of employees age 18-24 and 22% of employees age 25-33 leaving as compared to 10% of employees age 34-44 and 12% of employees age 45-55 leaving.

CaseStudy2$Age_factor = cut(CaseStudy2$Age, breaks = c(18,25,33,45,55,100), labels = c("18-24","25-33","34-44","45-54","55 and Older"))

#Match NoSalary dataframe clean up to CaseStudy2

CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary <- read.csv("~/Desktop/CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary.csv")
CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$JobSatisfaction <- as.factor(CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$JobSatisfaction)
CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$EnvironmentSatisfaction <- as.factor(CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$EnvironmentSatisfaction)
CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$JobLevel <- as.factor(CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$JobLevel)
CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$JobInvolvement <- as.factor(CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$JobInvolvement)
CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$PerformanceRating <- as.factor(CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$PerformanceRating)
CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$RelationshipSatisfaction <- as.factor(CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$RelationshipSatisfaction)
CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$StockOptionLevel <- as.factor(CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$StockOptionLevel)
CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$WorkLifeBalance <- as.factor(CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$WorkLifeBalance)
CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$Education <- as.factor(CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$Education)

#removing unnecessary columns
#Employee Count is all 1
CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$EmployeeCount <- NULL

#Employee Number is an unnecessary ID number
CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$EmployeeNumber <- NULL

#All employees are Over18
CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$Over18 <- NULL

#All Employee Standard Hours are 80
CaseStudy2CompSetNoSalary$StandardHours <-NULL

#Create prediction column and csv file
